S6_Notes: kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez. Additional recommendation measures on top of self-isolation. Citizens recommended against using public transport during peak hours, and against visiting sport centers, and other public events
St. Petersburg bans all gatherings with 50+ people. https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez

S3_Notes: kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez. A ban on all public events in St. Petersburg with greater than 1000 people (In Leningrad Oblast a ban on events with more than 300 people)

S1_Notes: Optional school attendance -- government recommends online learning https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4290063?from=main_1. https://icmos.ru/news/sobyanin-usilil-mery-po-protivodeystviyu-koronavirusu.
S2_Notes: Individuals required to self-isolate banned from coming into workplace http://kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez
S3_Notes: https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez Ban on all mass outdoor public events until April 10th. Indoor events should restricted to 50 people. (Moscow). A ban on all sports events with participation of international athletes.
S4_Notes: https://iz.ru/988083/2020-03-18/eksperty-otcenili-mery-borby-s-koronavirusom-na-moskovskom-transporte No restrictions on public transport. However, in-person ticket sales (within public transport vehicles) stopped.
S5_Notes: https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4290524 Prime Minister announces a plan to roll out a public information campaign about the coronavirus progression in the near future
S7_Notes: kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez. Travel restrictions to/from EU countries + Switzerland and Norway; Closure of border with Belarus

S2_Notes: Closure of all theaters, museums, cinemas, circuses, orchestras. Announced by Ministry of Culture. However, no general notice about closing workplaces and working from home http://kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez
S3_Notes: https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez All sports championships cancelled until April 10th (Ministry of Sports)
S6_Notes: Closure of all theaters, museums, cinemas, circuses, orchestras. Announced by Ministry of Culture.  http://kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez
S8_Notes:
17th March Government announces a 300Bn Rubles (3996779330.542231 USD) package as a stimulus for economy ('anti-crisis fund'). Particularly to support small - mid-sized business in affected industries (e.g. transport, aviation, tourism). Proposed tax-cuts and soft-loans.

In Moscow, Mayor Sergei Sobyanin said all state schools, sports schools and further education institutions in the city would be closed from March 21 until April 12. 
Source: https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-moscow-events/russia-bans-entry-to-foreign-nationals-closes-schools-idUSKBN21329T
S6_Notes: Closure of all fitness centers (gyms, swimming pools) in Moscow). https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez

Russian schools will go on a three-week vacation from March 23 to April 12 to prevent the spread of coronavirus, Education Minister Sergei Kravtsov said.
Source: https://ria.ru/20200318/1568763110.html
S7_Notes: Flight restrictions to Trukey, Vietnan, Thaliland, Indonesia and Japan. https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez
S10_Notes: Government invests 10 billion rubles for increasing diagnostic + treatment capacity. https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4299486
S11_Notes: Government invests 23 billion rubles to support pharmaceutical companies, after announcement that Russia started testing vaccines against the coronavirus on 20.03. https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4285154?from=doc_vrez https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4299486

S5_Notes: From the 24th of March government will share daily updates on hospital preparedness to combat the virus with the public. https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4299486

S8_Notes: Putin Emergency Address 25th March makes suggestions for economic stimulus, yet to be confirmed date of commencement. Said that fiscal stimulus will be expanded and will target low income households and SMEs. On the tax revenue side, small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) will receive a 6-month tax holiday (except VAT), the payroll tax rate for SMEs will be irreversibly lowered from 30% to 15% (for the portion of the salaries exceeding the minimum monthly wage of c.US$150). https://web.archive.org/web/20200330132838/http:/en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/63061

S1_Notes: Healthcare and education decisions are made at the provincial, not federal level, and there are considerable variation in different provincial strategies. I believe the first province to close schools was Ontario on the 12th, followed by Quebec on the 13th. Some provinces are recommending closures, some are doing mandatory closures by executive order.

Government statement: ‚ÄúThe ministries recommend that employees remain at home on a low-threshold basis if they have returned from an area affected by the coronavirus epidemic or experience flu symptoms.  In addition, it is recommended that employees be allowed, upon their notification, to work remotely for a period of time deemed necessary by the employer, for example.‚Äù
-	https://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/artikkeli/-/asset_publisher/1271139/suositus-sosiaali-ja-terveydenhuollon-seka-oppilaitosten-henkilostolle-ja-tyonantajille-koronavirustilanteessa 
Government statement: ‚ÄúThe Government recommends that employees returning from areas affected by the epidemic make arrangements for returning to work after a period of absence (two weeks) together with their employer. Employees are advised to work remotely if their tasks can be carried out from home. It is also advisable to discontinue non-essential work-related travel and to postpone holiday travel.‚Äù
-	https://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/artikkeli/-/asset_publisher/10616/hallitus-paatti-suosituksista-koronaviruksen-leviamisen-hillitsemiseksi
S3_Notes:
Government statement: 'The Government recommends that all public events with more than 500 attendees be cancelled until the end of May. Organisers of other events are also advised to consider, based on their risk assessments, whether or not to organise similar events. All major seminars and events organised by the state will be cancelled until the end of May.'
-	https://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/artikkeli/-/asset_publisher/10616/hallitus-paatti-suosituksista-koronaviruksen-leviamisen-hillitsemiseksi 
Government statement: ‚ÄúThe regional state administrative agencies will decide on the prohibition of public meetings or events in their area.‚Äù

Information provided on government website: ‚ÄúThe premises of schools, educational institutions, universities and universities of applied sciences as well as civic education and other liberal education institutes will be closed down, and contact teaching will be suspended. As an exception, however, pre-primary education organised in schools and contact teaching for grades 1‚Äì3 will continue for the children of parents working in sectors critical to the functioning of society. A further exception is that contact teaching will continue to be arranged for pupils who require it according to a decision on special-needs support; however, parents and guardians who are able to arrange childcare at home are still requested to do so.‚Äù

S8_Notes: Economic Stimulus Package 2020 announced; 3-pronged approach - first, to ease the cash flow of affected businesses; second, to assist affected individuals; and third, to stimulate demand for travel and tourism. Among the measures announced, hotels, travel agencies, airlines, shopping malls, convention and exhibition centres will get a 15% discount on monthly electricity bills for six months beginning April;  Taxi drivers, tourist bus drivers, tour guides and registered trishaw riders will be given RM600 each; Given the sudden decline in tourism, especially tourist arrivals from China, the stimulus also looks at pushing domestic tourism by giving Malaysians RM100 vouchers for flights, rail travel and hotel stays. This is on top of a RM1,000 tax relief for expenses made on domestic tourism [https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysias-interim-pm-mahathir-unveils-66b-economic-stimulus-package]
S10_Notes: The Ministry of Health has committed RM150 million to purchase the relevant equipment, medicine and consumables in the effort to contain the Covid-19 outbreak; Government staff on the front lines of the outbreak, such as doctors and medical personnel involved in containment efforts, will be eligible for a special monthly critical allowance of RM400 while immigration and related front-line workers will receive RM200 from February until the end of the outbreak. [https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/mahathir-unveils-66b-economic-stimulus-package]

S7_Notes: Ban on arrivals from Iran. People who have been in Iran must spend 14 days in a third country before seeking to enter Australia. https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-29/australia-announces-iran-travel-ban/12013884

S10_Notes:
The Australian Government has unveiled a comprehensive $2.4 billion health package to protect all Australians, including vulnerable groups such as the elderly, those with chronic conditions and Indigenous communities, from the coronavirus (COVID-19).

The package provides unprecedented support across primary care, aged care, hospitals, research and the national medical stockpile. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/24-billion-health-plan-fight-covid-19

S8_Notes: AUD17.8 billion stimulus package: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-12/federal-government-coronavirus-economic-stimulus/12042972

S3_Notes: Recommendations on public gatherings to come into effect as of 16 March https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/advice-coronavirus

Based on the expert medical advice of the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC), Commonwealth, State and Territory governments have agreed to provide public advice against holding non-essential, organised public gatherings of more than 500 people from Monday 16th March 2020. The recommendation to advise against non-essential, organised public gatherings of more than 500 people is precautionary and designed to reduce community transmission of COVID-19 in Australia. https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/advice-coronavirus
S7_Notes: All overseas arrivals to self-isolate for 14 days: https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2020/03/coronavirus-covid-19-what-you-need-to-know_2.pdf

S1_Notes: Some private schools closing: https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/17/coronavirus-school-closures-dozens-of-australian-private-schools-move-to-online-learning
The National Cabinet has accepted the advice of the AHPPC that schools should remain open at this time: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures
S3_Notes: The National Cabinet has accepted the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) advice that non-essential indoor gatherings of greater than 100 people (including staff) will no longer be permitted from Wednesday 18 March 2020. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures This does not apply to essential activities such as public transportation facilities, medical and health care facilities, pharmacies, emergency service facilities, correctional facilities, youth justice centres or other places of custody, courts or tribunals, Parliaments, food markets, supermarkets and grocery stores, shopping centres, office buildings, factories, construction sites, and mining sites, where it is necessary for their normal operation (although other social distancing and hygiene practices may be required in these settings).
S4_Notes:
National Cabinet agreed that public transport is essential and that AHPPC advice should apply in relation to public transport (trains, trams, buses, ferries), taxi and ride share vehicles and transport of vulnerable populations, with particular attention given to cleaning and hygiene.

National Cabinet agreed that domestic air travel is low risk. The issue of where people are travelling to and sensitive locations where travel should be restricted, will be developed with advice of states and territories. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures
S7_Notes:
Advice to all Australians - regardless of your destination, age or health - is do not travel overseas at this time. This our highest travel advice setting ‚Äì Level 4 of 4.
We also now advise Australians who are overseas who wish to return to Australia, to do so as soon as possible by commercial means. Commercial options may quickly become limited.
Anyone arriving in Australia from overseas, including Australians citizens and permanent residents, will be required to self-isolate for 14 days from the date of arrival. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures
S8_Notes: Aviation industry funding: The total cost of the measures are estimated to be AUD$715 million, with an upfront estimated benefit of $159 million to our airlines for reimbursement of applicable charges paid by domestic airlines since 1 February 2020. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures

S6_Notes: Tasmania announces border controls from 21 March - arrivals to self-isolate for 14 days: https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/19/tasmania-effectively-closes-borders-to-mainland-australia-in-response-to-coronavirus
S7_Notes:
Australia is closing its borders to all non-citizens and non-residents.
The entry ban takes effect from 9pm AEDT Friday, 20 March 2020, with exemptions only for Australian citizens, permanent residents and their immediate family, including spouses, legal guardians and dependants: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/border-restrictions

S3_Notes: Indoor gatherings of fewer than 100 people and outdoor gatherings of fewer than 500 people may proceed provided there is sufficient space for social distancing. Space requirements set out at: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-0
S8_Notes: AUD$444.6 million worth of funding from the Commonwealth Government for aged care. https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-0

S10_Notes: The Australian Government will provide $13 million to fast-track research into treatments for the novel coronavirus, COVID-19.  https://www.health.gov.au/ministers/the-hon-greg-hunt-mp/media/fast-tracking-research-into-treatments-for-covid-19?fbclid=IwAR2kyoO8XyfLjIDPUuAWRd7THm4GqJI2S4BY9u4PKn3l9NlFkCI7Y1h2ZCY

S1_Notes: Prime Minister says schools remain open, but parents can keep children at home if they wish. School closures announced in some states (Victoria, ACT, and forecast in NSW). Victoria: On Sunday 22 March, the Premier announced additional steps to combat the spread of the coronavirus (COVID-19), including bringing forward the school holidays in Victoria to commence from Tuesday 24 March. Early childhood education and care services, TAFE and training providers will remain open. (https://www.education.vic.gov.au/about/department/Pages/coronavirus.aspx). Australian Capital Territory schools to be pupil-free from 24/3/20: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/coronavirus-covid19-how-canberra-schools-will-operate/12080248
S8_Notes: AUD66.1 billion stimulus package: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/supporting-australian-workers-and-business
S11_Notes: AUD10million from Queensland Govt, AUD3 million from Federal Government and AUD3.5 million from Paul Ramsay Foundation (USD figure given for government funding only): https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-22/coronavirus-vaccine-funding-university-queensland-cases/12079184

S1_Notes: NSW Premier says schools in the state will remain open, but has encouraged parents to keep their children at home to contain the spread of coronavirus: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-23/coronavirus-parents-told-to-keep-children-home-from-school/12079524

S2_Notes: Australians encouraged to work from home where possible. A range of businesses must cease operating on 25/3, including some entertainment venues, beauty services, casinos, theatres, amusement parks, gyms, swimming pools, galleries, libraries: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-24-March-2020
S6_Notes: Northern Territory, Queensland, Western Australia and South Australia enforce border controls: arrivals from interstate required to self-isolate for 14 days: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-24/nt-border-restrictions-begin-amid-coronavirus-crisis/12086306 and https://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/south-australia-closes-borders/3978380/ and http://statements.qld.gov.au/Statement/2020/3/24/border-control-slows-virus-spread, and https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/coronavirus-covid-19-state-of-emergency-declarations.
S7_Notes: Ban on Australians travelling overseas: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/update-coronavirus-measures-24-March-2020

S8_Notes: AUD1.1 billion package for mental health services, domestic violence support, Medicare assistance for people at home and emergency food relief. See Prime Minister's media release: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/11-billion-support-more-mental-health-medicare-and-domestic-violence-services-0

The Australian Government will provide a wage subsidy to around 6 million workers who will receive a flat payment of $1,500 per fortnight through their employer, before tax. The $130 billion JobKeeper payment will help keep Australians in jobs and tackle the significant economic impact from the coronavirus. See Prime Minister's media release: https://www.pm.gov.au/media/130-billion-jobkeeper-payment-keep-australians-job

S2_Notes: The Administrative and Recruitment Affairs Organization ruled that telecommuting of government employees would be permissible.
S3_Notes:
The Ministry of Islamic Culture and Guidance announced the cancellation of all concerts and other cultural events for one week.
The Ministry of Sports and Youth took steps to cancel sporting events, including football matches.
S4_Notes: President Hassan Rouhani ordered the Ministry of Roads and Urban Development to make decisions about public commuting.
S5_Notes:
Iranian Cyber Police announced that to stop spreading photos and videos that are untrue and fake on COVID-19, notices were given to 118 people and 24 others were arrested.
The government created an application and a website to combat the outbreak.
S6_Notes: Iran's health minister announced that checkpoints would be placed between cities to limit travel. The government indicated that it may use force to limit travel between cities.
S8_Notes: The Management and Planning Organization announced the government has allocated 5 trillion rials to combat the virus.

20th March The government on Friday redirected $40 million non-utilised sums from World Bank projects that can be used by the federal and provincial government to battle the coronavirus, announced Minister for Economic Affairs Hammad Azhar. According to the breakdown shared by the minister, Punjab has $7.5 million, Sindh has $10 million, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa has 7 million, Balochistan has 2 million, while the federal government has $13.5 million.

Link: http://www.economia.gov.br/noticias/2020/marco/governo-anuncia-medidas-de-cooperacao-para-estados-e-municipios-para-o-combate-a-pandemia

S1_Notes: No federal policy on school closure, but most schools in Brazil remain closed due to measues adopted by state governors and mayors
S4_Notes: City of Rio de Janeiro suspends some bus lines. Ferries and trains can only be used by essential workers: https://oglobo.globo.com/rio/coronavirus-novo-decreto-de-crivella-comeca-valer-nesta-terca-veja-que-muda-no-rio-24324051
S6_Notes:
State of S√£o Paulo is put in quarantine from March 24 until April 7 and non-essential business are closed (Decree No. 64881/020): http://www.capital.sp.gov.br/noticia/governo-decreta-quarentena-em-todos-os-municipios-do-estado-de-sao-paulo-a-partir-da-proxima-terca-feira and https://www.saopaulo.sp.gov.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/decreto-quarentena.pdf

City o Rio de Janeiro closes businesses and restricts the circulation of people in the city: https://oglobo.globo.com/rio/coronavirus-novo-decreto-de-crivella-comeca-valer-nesta-terca-veja-que-muda-no-rio-24324051
S7_Notes:
Brazil suspends the entry of foreigners flying from several countries: China, EU, Iceland, Norway, Switzerland, UK, Northern Irland, Australia, Iran, Japan, Malaysia and South Korea
Link: https://www.novo.justica.gov.br/news/portaria-atualiza-restricoes-para-entrada-de-estrangeiros-no-pais-por-via-aerea and http://www.in.gov.br/en/web/dou/-/portaria-n-133-de-23-de-marco-de-2020-249317436

S6_Notes:
Some state governors announce they will enforce social isolation policies. Link: https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/politica/noticia/2020-03/governadores-manterao-medidas-de-isolamento-social-contra-covid-19

The City of Porto Alegre prohibits people over 60 years old told not to leave home unless 'when strictly necessary'. Link: https://www2.portoalegre.rs.gov.br/portal_pmpa_novo/default.php?p_noticia=999208905&PREVISAO+DE+PAUTAS:+QUARTA-FEIRA,+25+DE+MARCO
S8_Notes:
Another R$ 3,4 billion is added to the package to support the Ministry of Science and Technonolgy, Ministry of International Relations, and Ministry of Defence. The total is up to R$ 306,2 billion, with R$12,5 billion to healthcare (S10).

Link: http://www.economia.gov.br/noticias/2020/marco/confira-as-medidas-tomadas-pelo-ministerio-da-economia-em-funcao-do-covid-19-coronavirus

S2_Notes: State of Mato Grosso closes all non-essential businesses: https://agenciabrasil.ebc.com.br/saude/noticia/2020-03/veja-medidas-que-cada-estado-esta-adotando-para-combater-covid-19
S5_Notes: Ministry of Health launches WhatsApp channel to answer questions related to Covid-19. Link: https://www.saude.gov.br/noticias/agencia-saude/46607-ministerio-da-saude-lanca-canal-para-atender-populacao-no-whatsapp
S7_Notes:
Brazil prohibts the entry of foreigners of all nationalities throught its ports (by ship, boat etc)
Link: https://www.novo.justica.gov.br/news/portaria-restringe-a-entrada-de-estrangeiros-pelos-portos-brasileiros

S6_Notes: Federal government advices against closing businesses and social isolation, but most state governors do not lift restrictions
S7_Notes:
Brazil prohibts all foreigners from arriving or making a connection in a Brazilian airport if their country of nationality or their destination country has travel restrictions in place.
Link: https://www.novo.justica.gov.br/news/coronavirus-portaria-traz-novas-restricoes-para-entrada-de-estrangeiros-no-pais and http://www.in.gov.br/en/web/dou/-/portaria-n-149-de-27-de-marco-de-2020-250059813
S8_Notes:
The government publishes details of the R$ 40 billion line of credit which was alerady annouced in 25 March.
Link: http://www.economia.gov.br/noticias/2020/marco/governo-anuncia-r-40-bilhoes-em-linha-de-credito-para-garantir-empregos

S6_Notes: Federal Justice orders the suspension of the campaign commissioned by the federal government incentivising people to go outside: https://www.bbc.com/portuguese/brasil-52077132

S1_Notes: There is no policy at the national level, but schools across all 27 states in Brazil are registered as closed due to policies implemented by local governments: https://www.poder360.com.br/coronavirus/brasil-parado-saiba-o-que-esta-fechado-em-cada-unidade-da-federacao/?utm_source=meio&utm_medium=email

Starting on 25/02/2020, an online information campaign was launched on the official Government of Romania Facebook page on the 'Prevention and limitation of eventual infection with coronavirus'. New, updated information has since been provided daily on the facebook page (https://www.facebook.com/guv.ro). 

On the 24/02/2020, this campaign was announced: 'The information campaign of the population regarding the infection with COVID-19 will be extended, as well as the individual and collective prevention measures which should be taken and a daily newscast will be drafted regarding the development at international level and possible additional measures taken by the Romanian authorities' (https://www.nineoclock.ro/2020/02/24/pm-designate-orban-urges-romanians-to-learn-about-coronavirus-from-official-sources-only/)

On the 24/02/2020, this campaign was announced: 'The information campaign of the population regarding the infection with COVID-19 will be extended, as well as the individual and collective prevention measures which should be taken and a daily newscast will be drafted regarding the development at international level and possible additional measures taken by the Romanian authorities' (https://www.nineoclock.ro/2020/02/24/pm-designate-orban-urges-romanians-to-learn-about-coronavirus-from-official-sources-only/)

S8_Notes: !Unsure of start of implementation ! ‚ÄúHere are the four measures announced on Thursday:¬†The release of the so-called 'countercyclical capital buffer' banks have been required to keep on their books since the 2007 financial crisis. This will provide them an extra 200bn Danish kroner in liquidity, which they can either use to lend to businesses or to withstand losses on existing loans.¬†Two new loan guarantee schemes, one for large companies and one for small and medium enterprises (SMEs). The government will guarantee 70 percent of the value of any new bank loans given to SMEs who have seen operating profits fall by more than 50 percent. This could back up to 4.8bn kroner in new loans. It will guarantee 70 percent of the value of new loans to large companies who can demonstrate a fall in turnover over more than 50 percent. This could back 2.7bn kroner in new loans.¬†Employers from now on be completely reimbursed by the government from the first day¬†that an employee becomes ill or enters quarantine due to coronavirus, rather than having to themselves absorb the bill for the few days.¬†Employment legislation is being relaxed to allow companies to reduce employees hours temporarily, with the employees incomes then supplemented by unemployment benefit. The Ministry of Employment hopes that this will prevent employees from being laid off.‚Äù (source: https://www.thelocal.dk/20200313/denmark-moves-to-protect-economy-from-coronavirus-impact)

S7_Notes: Effective 12:00 p.m. on March 14 the government of Denmark closed its borders to all but Danish citizens, individuals with Danish work or residency permits, and those the Danish government determines have a critical purpose of travel (eg, someone commissioned to provide goods or services in Denmark). ¬†The closures will be in effect until April 13.

The ban will apply at least until 30 March 2020. + The Government has ordered a temporary ban ‚Äì effective as from 18 March 2020 at 10.00 am ‚Äì on night clubs, discotheques, bars, pubs, hookah cafes etc. The ban will apply at least until 30 March 2020. + The Government has ordered a temporary ban ‚Äì effective as from 18 March 2020 at 10.00 am ‚Äì on serving guests at restaurants and cafes etc. It is still possible for restaurants and cafes etc. to sell take-away food and drinks etc. The ban will apply at least until 30 March 2020. S8_Notes:
Large economic stimulus package announced. The used estimate in USD is conservative. Description on IMF website: 'A package of fiscal measures was announced to contain the economic impact of the outbreak. The package includes spending measures of about 10-20 billion euros (1-2 percent of GDP) in the next three months, and covering (i) compensation of up to 90 percent of labor costs for companies expecting a reduction in revenues of 20 percent or more; (ii) compensation for affected sectors (hospitality, travel, and others); (iii) support for entrepreneurs and the self-employed; (iv) scaling up of the short-time working scheme (unemployment benefit compensation available to companies needing to reduce their staff by at least 20 percent). In addition, companies can defer tax payments without penalties, and calculate provisional taxes on the basis of expected reduced activity levels. Also, public guarantee schemes, especially for SME loans, are expanded to help the most vulnerable companies to manage their liquidity problems. The total cost of these programs will depend on demand.'
Government statement on this package: https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/actueel/nieuws/2020/03/17/coronavirus-kabinet-neemt-pakket-nieuwe-maatregelen-voor-banen-en-economie

The Jakarta Post
https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/05/covid-19-jakarta-suspends-mass-gathering-filming-permits-as-part-of-containment-measures.html
 The Jakarta city administration has temporarily suspended the issuance of permits for mass gatherings, including for film shooting purposes, as part of its COVID-19 containment efforts.
The administration through its One-Stop Integrated Services Agency (BPTSP) will stop issuing permits indefinitely following a 2020 instruction issued by Governor Anies Baswedan on March 3, a day after Indonesia reported its first confirmed COVID-19 cases.

S6_Notes: Government has prepared several plans to manage annual Eid al-Fitr exodus (‚Äúmudik‚Äù) during which people return to their hometowns across the country; measures to limit crowds and movement of individuals in certain areas
S8_Notes: 2nd Stimulus Package: Providing tax incentives and subsidies for workers, businesses and families affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. Fiscal stimulus measures: 1) Exempt manufacturing workers with yearly incomes below Rp 200 million from income tax for six months; 2) Import taxes for raw materials waived for six months for 19 manufacturing industries; 3) Corporate tax rate cut by 30 percent for six months for 19 manufacturing industries; 4) Repayment of overpaid tax to be sped up without initial audits. No limit set for exporters, but Rp 5 billion limit set for non-exporters.
S10_Notes: Finance Minister stated the readiness to allocate the budget based on the Ministry of Health‚Äôs funding requirement calculation; which would include medical equipments, mask distribution, etc. Import duty for medical devices will also be exempted.
S11_Notes: National spokesperson for COVID-19 stated that Indonesia is still unable to do the initial vaccine design due to limited specimens to look for a model. However, he stated that ‚Äúin terms of budget, Indonesia is ready to deal with (COVID-19)..‚Äù

On March 17, the Minister of Health announced the following measures which began on March 18 at 8:00am for a duration of two weeks:

Prohibition on all movement between governates.
Citizens may not leave home except in extreme circumstances.
Prohibition on gatherings of more than ten people.
Public transportation is suspended.
Malls and commercial complexes will be closed.
Surgeries and medical exams will be suspended except for urgent cases.

Government of Colombia creates the National Emergency Mitigation Fund of almost 1.5 billion USD (6 trillion Colombian Pesos). The government has adopted a series of measures to increase the investment in health care which have focused on redirecting funds that were previously planned for other ends. The national government also created a new fund called ‚ÄúEmergency Mitigation Fund‚Äù (FOME) destined to guarantee resources to finance the extraordinary health and economic measures associated with COVID. It is not clear how much is directed to specifically health care.

S8_Notes:
President Recep Tayyip Erdogan announced the package, which includes debt payment delays and tax cuts across various sectors, following a meeting on measures to counter the pandemic at Cankaya Palace in Ankara.
'Value added tax (VAT) on domestic airline flights has been cut to 1% from 18% for a period of three months,' Erdogan said.
He added that accommodation taxes will also not be applied until November.
Also, social security premiums and VAT deductions have been suspended for six months across various sectors, including retail, malls, iron-steel, automative, logistic and textile, he said.
Moreover, credit payments for firms who are facing cash flow disruptions due to coronavirus will be postponed for three months, he added.
'We will provide additional support to those companies when needed,' the president said.
He said credit payments of craftspeople and artisans to state lender Halkbank will also be delayed for three months without interest. 
In order to maintain capacity utilization rates, the government has decided to extend financial support to stocks for exporters, Erdogan added.
The country also doubled the credit guarantee fund's limit to 50 billion Turkish liras ($7.70 billion), up from 25 billion liras ($3.35 billion)

March 27, 2020 /PRNewswire/ -- Honduras President Juan Orlando Hern√°ndez announced the immediate roll out of an economic aid plan to fully address the main needs of the population amid the sanitary emergency caused by COVID-19 and its consequences. Since February, following the emergency declaration for dengue and coronavirus, Honduras approved a budgetary support of $4.4 million for the preparation of the imminent arrival of COVID-19 in Honduras.

Subsequently, President Hernandez lead the approval in Congress of the Economic Acceleration Law, which aims to immediately inject 420 million dollars into the national economy to boost the generation of 100,000 jobs, and to strengthen the social security system to guaranty assistance capacity to more than 3 million users. The initiative includes the construction and equipment of 95 health centers and 11 hospitals nationwide.  
SOURCE: https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/honduras-implements-economic-aid-plan-in-the-face-of-covid-19-emergency-301031238.html

S1_Notes: Kazakhstan closes all schools and colleges until April 5th. Colleges and universities to move to online learning. https://web.archive.org/save/https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/kazakhstan-suspends-all-public-events-over-coronavirus-2; https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.euractiv.com/section/central-asia/news/kazakhstan-takes-decisive-steps-to-stop-the-spread-of-coronavirus/
S7_Notes: Kazakhstan closes its borders for everyone, except returning citizens, diplomats, and those invited by government. Kazakhs are barred from leaving country. https://web.archive.org/web/20200330230909/https://24.kg/english/146852_Government_of_Kazakhstan_introduces_quarantine_regime_in_Nur-Sultan_and_Almaty__/; https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.bakermckenzie.com/en/insight/publications/2020/03/kazakhstan-state-of-emergency-covid19
S9_Notes: 'At its 16 March meeting, the National Bank of Kazakhstan decided to maintain the base rate at 12.00%' https://www.focus-economics.com/country-indicator/kazakhstan/interest-rate; https://tradingeconomics.com/kazakhstan/interest-rate

S4_Notes: A number of bus routes from Almaty suspended. May also shut down public service in Nur-Sultan in light of the quarantine https://web.archive.org/save/https://en.trend.az/business/transport/3210447.html; https://web.archive.org/web/20200330223535/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-kazakhstan-restrictio-idINR4N28J00V
S6_Notes: Government imposes lockdown on two cities Nur-Sultan and Almaty, effective starting Midnight 19th. Also, all stores and shopping malls in the two major cities will be closed and only grocery and drug stores will be allowed to operate during the quarantine. According to the website, special points to distribute food, medicine, and other items will be defined in Nur-Sultan and Almaty. https://web.archive.org/web/20200330225531/https://24.kg/english/146852_Government_of_Kazakhstan_introduces_quarantine_regime_in_Nur-Sultan_and_Almaty__/; https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.rferl.org/a/armenia-puts-restrictions-on-public-and-private-events-amid-spike-in-coronavirus-cases/30492284.html

Nur-Sultan and Almaty go on official lockdown. 'In addition to restricting movement of people and vehicles, the authorities have limited public transportation and instructed restaurants to switch to delivery-only service. To enforce the isolation of these city centres, the President announced the need to impose penalties on those who violate the requirements of quarantine.' https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.euractiv.com/section/central-asia/news/kazakhstan-takes-decisive-steps-to-stop-the-spread-of-coronavirus/

S11_Notes: Report that some institutes in Kazakhstan are working on developing a COVID-19 vaccine. 'Kazakhstan also started to develop the drug against the infection.  National center for biotechnology in Nur-Sultan together with the Research Institute for Biological Safety Problems has started working on the new antiviral vaccine.' Unclear if / how much funding they have received from the government. https://web.archive.org/save/https://kazakh-tv.kz/en/view/health/page_209741_countries-developing-vaccine-against-coronavirus

S8_Notes: 'Kazakhstan plans to spend $10 billion on a stimulus package aimed at softening the blow to its economy from the coronavirus outbreak and the collapse in the price of oil, the former Soviet republic's main export. The Nur-Sultan government said on Monday it would pay doctors involved in the anti-coronavirus campaign monthly bonuses of about $500 to $2000, depending on their qualifications and proximity to patients, as well as extra payouts in case of infection and disability or death caused by the virus.' https://web.archive.org/save/https://news.trust.org/item/20200330135910-l2scn/; https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-kazakhstan-budget/update-1-kazakhstan-to-tap-sovereign-fund-for-41-bln-to-finance-stimulus-idUSL8N2BM0BQ; https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.swfinstitute.org/news/78511/kazakhstan-government-to-tap-swf-to-help-with-economic-fallout-from-coronavirus-and-low-oil-prices

S8_Notes:
Suite of measures announced, no clear single figure/value -- All proposals can only be ratified by the National Assembly, and the National Treasury Cabinet Secretary Ukur Yatani has been directed to present them before Parliament for approval before April 1, 2020.

List of what was announced below, including tax reliefs and measures to help reduce financial uncertainty among Kenyans:

>100% tax relief to Kenyans earning Ksh24, 000 and below.
>Pay as you earn (PAYE) reduction from a maximum of 30% to 25%.
>Reduction of turnover tax rate from 3% to 1% for all micro, small and medium enterprises.
>Reduction of resident income tax to 25%.
>The Government to make available Ksh10 billion to vulnerable groups including the elderly and orphans, among others. This, the president, said will be done through cash transfers from the Ministry of Labour and Social Protection.
>Temporary suspension of the listing of loan defaulters with the Credit Reference Bureau (CRB) of any person, micro, small and medium enterprise and corporate entities whose loan account is in arrears effective April 1, 2020.
>Reduction of VAT from 16% to 14% effective April 1, 2020.
>All ministries and State departments to make payments amounting to Ksh30 billion to those owed monies by the Government. This, the president said, must be done within three weeks from March 25. The Head of State also urged the private sector to clear pending bills.
>KRA to expedite payment of all VAT refunds amounting to Ksh10 billion, or allow withholding of offsetting VAT. This, President Kenyatta said, must happen within three weeks.
>The president and his deputy to take 80% pay-cut, all Cabinet Secretaries to take 30% pay-cuts, Chief Administrative Secretaries (30%) and Principal Secretaries (20%).
>All State and public officers aged 50 and above; and have preexisting medical conditions, to take leave from work, or be allowed to work from home. This directive excludes those public officers working in the security department.
>Reduce the Cash Reserve Ratio from 5.25% to 4.25%. The president said this will help increase liquidity of Ksh35 billion to commercial banks, which, in turn, will be in positions to provide loan services to ‚Äúdistressed Kenyans‚Äù.
>CBK directed to provide flexibility to bank loan classifications and loans performing as at March 2, 2020.
S10_Notes:
To be ratified by the National Assembly, and the National Treasury Cabinet Secretary Ukur Yatani has been directed to present them before Parliament for approval before April 1, 2020.

Ksh1 billion from the Universal Health Coverage kitty be channeled to the employment of new health workers to help combat the spread of COVID-19.

'Travellers from any country with a single case of the virus have been barred from entering Kenya for the next 30 days.' (Mar 16 2020)
S8_Notes:
Suite of measures announced, no clear single figure/value -- All proposals can only be ratified by the National Assembly, and the National Treasury Cabinet Secretary Ukur Yatani has been directed to present them before Parliament for approval before April 1, 2020.

List of what was announced below, including tax reliefs and measures to help reduce financial uncertainty among Kenyans:

>100% tax relief to Kenyans earning Ksh24, 000 and below.
>Pay as you earn (PAYE) reduction from a maximum of 30% to 25%.
>Reduction of turnover tax rate from 3% to 1% for all micro, small and medium enterprises.
>Reduction of resident income tax to 25%.
>The Government to make available Ksh10 billion to vulnerable groups including the elderly and orphans, among others. This, the president, said will be done through cash transfers from the Ministry of Labour and Social Protection.
>Temporary suspension of the listing of loan defaulters with the Credit Reference Bureau (CRB) of any person, micro, small and medium enterprise and corporate entities whose loan account is in arrears effective April 1, 2020.
>Reduction of VAT from 16% to 14% effective April 1, 2020.
>All ministries and State departments to make payments amounting to Ksh30 billion to those owed monies by the Government. This, the president said, must be done within three weeks from March 25. The Head of State also urged the private sector to clear pending bills.
>KRA to expedite payment of all VAT refunds amounting to Ksh10 billion, or allow withholding of offsetting VAT. This, President Kenyatta said, must happen within three weeks.
>The president and his deputy to take 80% pay-cut, all Cabinet Secretaries to take 30% pay-cuts, Chief Administrative Secretaries (30%) and Principal Secretaries (20%).
>All State and public officers aged 50 and above; and have preexisting medical conditions, to take leave from work, or be allowed to work from home. This directive excludes those public officers working in the security department.
>Reduce the Cash Reserve Ratio from 5.25% to 4.25%. The president said this will help increase liquidity of Ksh35 billion to commercial banks, which, in turn, will be in positions to provide loan services to ‚Äúdistressed Kenyans‚Äù.
>CBK directed to provide flexibility to bank loan classifications and loans performing as at March 2, 2020.
S10_Notes:
To be ratified by the National Assembly, and the National Treasury Cabinet Secretary Ukur Yatani has been directed to present them before Parliament for approval before April 1, 2020.

Ksh1 billion from the Universal Health Coverage kitty be channeled to the employment of new health workers to help combat the spread of COVID-19.

'The Minister for Health, Community Development, Gender, Elderly and Children, Ms Ummy Mwalimu recently said authorities have expanded thermal screening facilities at all major airports.
The minister revealed that screening exercises for incoming passengers are conducted in major airports--Julius Nyerere International Airport (JNIA), Kilimanjaro Airport (KIA) and Mwanza Airport.
The minister said about 140 medical equipment had been installed at all major airports, borders and ports, and that medical experts have been trained to handle the screening process to reduce the risk of transmission from persons jetting in who might be infected.' -- https://allafrica.com/stories/202003140021.html

S4_Notes: Land Transport Regulate Authority and health experts have issued warnings in Tanzania about the potential for overcrowded city buses to spread coronavirus, particularly Mbagala and Gongolamboto routes in Dar es Salaam. Authorities have advised bus operators to limit the number of passengers and encourage hand washing before riding. DART in Dar es Salaam has created queues for passengers, increased the number of buses on busy routes, and opened hand washing facilities in bus stations. However, concerns remain that operators and passengers are not listening to these recommendations as public buses remain crowded. https://web.archive.org/web/20200326150955/https://allafrica.com/stories/202003260622.html
S7_Notes: 'As part of the additional measures to curb the spread of the virus, the president announced that with effect from today Tanzania will put all visitors and Tanzanians arriving from the high risk countries under quarantine at their own expense for 14 days.' -- https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/1840340-5500244-audo6y/index.html

DART in Dar es Salaam has created queues for passengers, increased the number of buses on busy routes, and opened hand washing facilities in bus stations. However, concerns remain that operators and passengers are not listening to these recommendations as public buses remain crowded. https://web.archive.org/web/20200326150955/https://allafrica.com/stories/202003260622.html

S2_Notes:
Excerpt from Premier Burt's speech on the 18th of March, 7pm with regard to government action in Bermuda from 19 March onwards: 
'The following Legal Affairs departments: National Drug Control and Child and Family Services, residential treatment services will remain in operation. All other departments in the Department of Legal Affairs will have reduced operations.
The public bus and ferry services are suspended until April 6. Government workers who are not directly involved with the COVID-19 management and operation will work from home until April 6th. Managers will provide guidance to all Public Officers throughout the course of the day tomorrow.
Private businesses are encouraged to ask their employees to work from home, if possible. Otherwise work schedules should be staggered to minimize the number of people in the workplace. Bars, restaurants, and other social establishments are strongly urged to scale down their operations from tonight and enforce social distancing. Essential retail outlets will continue to operate, such as food and medicines and there will be specific guidance issued to all retail establishments tomorrow following the COVID-19 EMO meeting.'
Sources: https://www.gov.bm/articles/premier-david-burt-statement-covid-19 & https://www.gov.bm/articles/emo-statement-19-march-2020

S4_Notes:
'Additionally, the public bus and ferry services are suspended until April 6' - http://www.caribbean360.com/news/airport-closing-seaport-only-allowing-cargo-public-transportation-services-curtailed-as-bermuda-records-first-covid-19-cases

Also appears on Status of Operations document of the government, updated to March 21: https://www.gov.bm/sites/default/files/11436_Coronavirus_2020_Status-of-Operations-Covid-19_Flyer.pdf

S3_Notes: Gatherings with more than 50 people are now banned and can be penalized if infringed upon this regulation https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.gov.bm/articles/closure-notice-enforcement-penalties

S2_Notes:
Government statement: 'The Minister of Health signed an Order on Friday closing all schools, tourist accommodation swimming pools, gyms, beauty salons, spas and barbers; as well church services (except funerals), sports club activities and concerts with more than 50 people.
To further reduce the risk of community spread Cabinet has approved the following further actions with effect from 5pm tomorrow, Monday March 23rd:
The Minister of Health will extend the closure Order to include retail stores, cinemas and bars and restaurants limited to take out service only. 
Enforced social distancing should will now be limited to gatherings of no more than 10 people. 
The Royal Bermuda Regiment and the Bermuda Police Service will be engaged in operations directly aimed at enforcing required quarantine of persons who arrived in Bermuda since 17th March. 
Essential businesses only will be permitted to open and will be required to adopt the aggressive social distancing guidance now in place and on reduced hours. These businesses are banks, food suppliers or supermarkets, pharmacies and gas stations.'

Source: https://www.gov.bm/articles/covid-19-update-22-march-2020 & https://www.gov.bm/articles/covid-19-update-23-march-2020
S3_Notes: Social distancing is now intensified by banning gatherings with more than 10 people https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.gov.bm/articles/covid-19-update-22-march-2020

'Increasing Communications': The Department of Communications continues to look for ways to get information about COVID-19 to the public.

Starting today for two hours each day 12pm ‚Äì 1pm and 5pm ‚Äì 6pm - Monday to Friday, there will be live content on the Emergency Broadcast station ‚Äì 100.1.

The Government television station CITV currently covers all press conferences live and provides COVID-19 updates six times a day for one hour. All government press conferences are broadcast on the various cable providers‚Äô

 local channels. You can also watch the press conferences live on CITV, Facebook, YouTube, and gov.bm. The Communications team is working to make sure every demographic in Bermuda has access to the information provided by Government. Prime Minister announces a two-week 'lockdown' in which citizens must stay at home, but there is a lack of detail. See Radio NZ article quoting PM: ''Starting Tuesday 24th of March this country will come to a lockdown for a period of 14 days,' he said.

'This step is absolutely necessary for us to make sure that every citizen remains where they are. I do not intend to raise hype and tension and panic. It is just about you staying at home so we can take stock,' he said.

Mr Marape said more meetings would be held today to further define the national Covid-19 response strategy before more announcements are made about expectations for public behaviour during the lockdown.' https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412357/coronavirus-png-announces-lockdown-solomons-closes-border-to-non-citizens.
